<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-payroll-tax-filing-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Payroll tax filing in QuickBooks, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Every time you run payroll in QuickBooks Online Payroll, the software calculates the taxes tied to that pay run &mdash; the amounts withheld from each employee&rsquo;s wages and the amounts the business owes as an employer. <em>Filing</em> is the separate step of reporting those amounts to the IRS and the states on the right forms, on the right schedule, and <em>paying</em> them. For subscribers on Intuit&rsquo;s full-service tiers (Premium and Elite), Intuit&rsquo;s payroll service does that filing and payment automatically: it makes the tax deposits on schedule, files the quarterly and annual returns, and produces year-end forms. On lower or self-service tiers you may handle some filings yourself; the page below explains how to keep either path correct.</p>
      <p>The thing to understand is that QuickBooks files what you tell it to file. If a work location, an employee&rsquo;s filing status, a state tax-account ID, or the deposit schedule is set up wrong, the calculation is wrong &mdash; and Intuit files the wrong number on your behalf, which surfaces later as a notice, a penalty, or a year-end form that doesn&rsquo;t match the wages. That&rsquo;s the gap an independent ProAdvisor firm closes: correct setup, payroll liabilities reconciled against the general ledger so the books tie, and problems caught early. We don&rsquo;t file your payroll taxes ourselves &mdash; that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s service for subscribers &mdash; and a complex or multi-state filing situation may still need a CPA or a dedicated payroll specialist.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

