<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-payroll-tax-filing-operator">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">When a ProAdvisor should help</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">When a ProAdvisor should help with payroll tax filing.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Intuit&rsquo;s service files and pays payroll taxes for subscribers, so the ProAdvisor&rsquo;s job isn&rsquo;t to file &mdash; it&rsquo;s to make sure what Intuit files is correct and that the books behind it tie. A Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor with active Online and Desktop certifications confirms work locations, employee filing statuses, state and local tax-account IDs, and the deposit schedule are right; reconciles the payroll liability accounts against the general ledger every period; and catches a mismatch &mdash; between the payroll subledger, the liabilities, and the bank &mdash; before it becomes a notice. That work happens against a written scope. What stays with Intuit is the filing and payment itself, a question about a specific deposit Intuit scheduled, or anything inside your Intuit subscription. And a genuinely complex situation &mdash; multi-state employees, a fast-changing nexus footprint, equity or fringe-benefit complexity, or back-tax exposure &mdash; may need a CPA or a dedicated payroll specialist; we&rsquo;ll say so plainly rather than stretch beyond bookkeeping. Independent firm &mdash; not Intuit, and not Intuit&rsquo;s software support.</p>
